Interesting Observations:

¶

  • The distribution for age seems to be normally distributed,where most patients fall within the middle range of ages, and fewer patients are found at the extreme young and old ages.

  • Trestbps seems to seems to be normally distributed, This implies that a significant number of patients have resting blood pressure values clustered around the mean, while fewer patients have either very low or very high resting blood pressure values.

  • Chol also seems to be normally distributed,This indicates that a significant number of patients have cholesterol levels close to the mean value, while fewer patients have exceptionally low or high cholesterol levels.
  • Thalach seems sightly left skewed,This means that more patients have maximum heart rates that are slightly lower than the mean, with fewer patients achieving very high heart rates. This could potentially reflect the typical response of patients during exercise.
  • oldpeak seems to be right skewed,This means that more patients have higher levels of ST depression, potentially indicating a greater degree of cardiac stress during exercise for a subset of patients.

# Get a list of attributes to visualize
cat_cols_viz = ['cp','fbs','restecg','exang','slope','ca','thal']


# Set style
sns.set_style('whitegrid')

# Set up subplot to display graphs
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=4, figsize=(20,10), sharex=False, sharey=False)
plt.suptitle('Distribution of Our Categorical Features by target', 
             fontsize=30, fontweight='bold', y=1.032)

# Initialize row and column index iterators in preparation for filling in the subplot
row_iterator = 0
col_iterator = 0

# Fill in the subplot
for col in cat_cols_viz:
    # Adjust indices once we reach the end of a row (moving from left to right)
    if col_iterator == 4:
        col_iterator = 0
        row_iterator = row_iterator + 1
    
    
    # Initialize value count series
    valCount_series = disease[col].value_counts()
    target_valCount_series = disease[disease.target=='Heart Disease'][col].value_counts()
    
    
    # Create the barplot (in blue) depicting customer count--by column
    sns.barplot(x=valCount_series.index, y=valCount_series.values, color='lightskyblue', ax=axes[row_iterator][col_iterator])
    
    # Create the barplot (in orange) depicting customer churn count--by column
    sns.barplot(x=target_valCount_series.index, y=target_valCount_series.values, color='khaki', ax=axes[row_iterator][col_iterator])

    # Label the graph
    axes[row_iterator][col_iterator].set_title('%s' % col, fontsize=20)
        
    # Rotate xlabels
    plt.sca(axes[row_iterator, col_iterator])
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right', rotation_mode='anchor')    
    
    # Increment row and column indices
    col_iterator = col_iterator + 1
    # Remove the empty subplot at the last position
fig.delaxes(axes[1, 3])

    
# Adjust spacing of subplot
fig.tight_layout()

import os
estimator = RF.estimators_[0]

with tempfile.TemporaryDirectory() as temp_dir:
    # Visualize the selected tree using Graphviz
    dot_data = export_graphviz(estimator, out_file=None,
                               feature_names=X.columns,
                               class_names=['No Disease', 'Disease'],
                               filled=True, rounded=True,
                               special_characters=True)
    graph = graphviz.Source(dot_data)
    
output_path = os.path.join(temp_dir, "random_forest_tree")
    
    # Save the visualization as a PNG image in the temporary directory
graph.render(filename=output_path, format="png")
    
    # Open the tree visualization
graph.view(filename=output_path)
